awk -F ":" ' $3>=1000 { print $1, $3 }'  usersfile  ==> prints username and id value greater than 1000

vim editor:
==========
vim <file name>         ==> opens the file and if file is not there, it will create one and opens directly.

Colon mode:
============

:q                                                                => quit
:q!                                                               => quit without saving changes
:wq                                                               => save and quit
:set nu                                                           => Display line numbers
:<Line Number>                                                    => Cursor goes to the line number
:/<word to search>                                                => Top to bottom
:?<word to search>                                                => Bottom to Top
:<Line number>/d                                                  => delete line
:%d                                                               => Delete everything
:noh                                                              => don't highlight
:<Line numbers>s/<word to find>/<word to replace/                 => replaces first occurence in the line
:<Line numbers>s/<word to find>/<word to replace/g                => replaces all occurence in the line
:%s/<word to find>/<word to replace/                              => replaces all occurence in the all lines


Esc Mode:
=========

gg                                                               => Takes to top of the file
Shift+g                                                          => Takes bottom to top
u                                                                => undo
Ctrl+r                                                           => redo
dd                                                               => deletes line
yy                                                               => copy the line
p                                                                => pastes below that line
Shift+p                                                          => pastes above that line


CRUD:
=====
USER Management:
================

user group role permission

useradd <user name>
id <user name>
cat /etc/passwd   => all users info

groupadd <group name>
cat /etc/group    => display group info

usermod -g  <group name> <user name>  => Change primary group
usermod -aG <group name> <user name>  => user has been Append secondary group

Command	     Meaning	                    Risk
usermod -g	Change primary group	        Medium
usermod -G	Replace all secondary groups	High
usermod -aG	Append secondary group	      Safe âœ…


passwd <user name>  => to set password for user

Default Key based authentications only enabled. /etc/ssh/sshd_config   => ssh configs are here
Enable PasswordAuthentication to yes ==>
sshd -t  => check config file syntax errors
systemctl restart sshd  ==> To get the changes effected

Giving sudo access to users
/etc/sudoers
for specific permissions add here in this file, then the user will have that permissions only instead of all sudo permissions.
if you want to give full permissions just add user to sudo group.

gpasswd -d <user name> <group name>   => removing user from a group

Compression .zip for windows and .tar.gz for Linux

tar -cf <file name>.tar.gz  <folder to compress>  => creating zip
tar -xf <file name>.tar.gz   => extracting

usermod -L <user name>  => To Lock the user access
userdel -r <user name>  => Deletes the user
























